actually widened the racial divides. Policing the Racial Divide tells story of how race, despite the best intentions, often dominates the way policing unfolds in cities across America.Drawing on in-depth interviews and hundreds of hours of ethnographic observation, Gordon offers a behind-the-scenes account of how the police are reconfiguring segregated landscapes. She illuminates an underexplored source of racially disparate policing: the role of law enforcement in urban growth politics. Many postindustrial cities are increasing the divisions of segregation, Gordon argues, by investing in downtowns, gentrified neighborhoods, and entertainment corridors, while framing marginalized central city neighborhoods as sources of criminal and civic threat that must be contained and controlled. Gordon paints a sobering picture of modern-day segregation, and how the police enforce its racial borders, showing us two separate, unequal sides of the same city: one where rich, white neighborhoods are protected, and another where poor, Black neighborhoods are punished.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEqualityzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aPolicezUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aPolice-community relationszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aSegregationzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aUrban policyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aUrbanizationxSocial aspectszUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  aCommunity policing.  aEthnography.  aGentrification.  aGrowth politics.  aLocalism.  aNeighborhood inequality.  aNeoliberal Urbanism.  aOver-policing.  aPolice districts.  aPolice redistricting.  aPolice reform.  aPolice service.  aPolicing strategy.  aPolicing.  aPostindustrial.  aProactive policing.  aProblem-solving policing.  aRace out of place.  aRace.  aRacial 